Both merges are fast-forward merges because the develop branch did not receive any new commits after neat_branch and messy_branch were created. Since develop was still pointing to an older commit that was directly behind the tip of each feature branch, Git did not need to create a separate merge commit. Instead, Git simply “fast-forwarded” (moved) the develop branch pointer up to the latest commit on neat_branch, and later up to the latest commit on messy_branch, resulting in a straight, linear history.
